5.  Environmental economist (national, 5 person-months). The environmental economist 
will  support  the  national  team  leader  and  will  have  (i)  an  advanced  university  degree  in 
environmental economics, with at least 8 years of relevant experience; (ii) a good understanding 
of environmental issues in the PRC and eco-compensation approaches; and (iii) demonstrated 
experience in similar assignments. The economist will have the following specific responsibilities: 
(i)  function as the leading expert on pilot studies;  
(ii)  review existing national methodologies and the eco-compensation mechanism 
and rates for estimating forest and grassland ecosystem services; 
(iii)  provide recommendations for the development of estimating forest and grassland 
ecosystem services in Gansu Province;  
(iv)  conduct a rapid assessment of ecosystem services and key economic values of 
forests and grasslands in Gansu Province through selection of two pilot study 
areas;  
(v)  provide (a) a comprehensive report, with recommendations on eco-compensation 
approaches;  (b)  rates  for  forests  and  grasslands,  considering  the  wider 
ecosystem services; (c) implications for water resources management; and (d) 
current land use and management approaches, including protection regimes and 
implications; 
(vi)  give presentations during workshops and seminars; 
(vii)  provide input into TA inception, interim, and final reports; and 
(viii)  provide input into other related technical tasks as assigned by the national TA 
team leader.  

6.  Forestry eco-compensation specialist (national, 5 person-months). The specialist will 
support the national environmental economist and will have (i) an advanced university degree in 
environmental economics, with at least 5 years of relevant experience; (ii) a good understanding 
of environmental issues in the PRC and forest-related eco-compensation approaches; and (iii) 
demonstrated experience in similar assignments. The specialist will have the following specific 
responsibilities: 
(i)  support the national environmental economist in implementing the pilot studies 
and  conducting  the  review  of  existing  methodology  for  assessing  forest 
ecosystem services; 
(ii)  provide individual review reports on compensation rate, payment vehicles, and 
compensation mechanisms for forest-related eco-compensation; 
(iii)  participate in the TA inception, midterm, and final workshops, and provide inputs 
needed for preparation of the TA inception, midterm, and final reports;
